{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521101","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521101"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:31:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:31:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13549"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13549","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13549"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.05,0.22,0.38,0.29]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6164"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48874"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6164","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6164"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13549"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33869"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1595"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11286"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12225"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15838"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48874","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48874"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man is in the Emergency Department after a massive inferior myocardial infarction. He is registered as an organ donor, and this is confirmed with his next of kin. Despite optimal medical management as per the Advanced Life Support guidelines, he has no signs of improvement, and has remained unconscious (GCS 3).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis loved ones make the decision to proceed with organ donation, after circulatory death has been formally determined.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EActive treatment and cardiorespiratory support (including CPR and intubation) are withdrawn. The patient has an arterial line in-situ, which shows absent arterial pulsatility for five minutes. An ECG shows asystole over this same period. There is no palpable carotid pulse, and on auscultation there is no breath or heart sounds.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"The presence of which one of the following findings on examination is NOT required for the diagnosis of \u0022circulatory death\u0022 in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Absent heart sounds on auscultation","Absent central pulse","Asystole for five minutes on an ECG","Absent arterial pulsatility for five minutes using an arterial line","No evidence of breathing"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAs determined by the The Australian and New Zealand Intensive Care Society (ANZICS) guidelines, circulatory death requires an absence of circulation for five minutes, in addition to an absence of breathing and spontaneous movement. If an arterial line is present, the absence of circulation is determined by five minutes of absent arterial pulsatility using intra-arterial pressure monitoring and confirmed with clinical examination (e.g. absent heart sounds and/or absent central pulse). If there is no arterial line, electrical asystole should be observed for five minutes on the electrocardiogram and confirmed by clinical examination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo minimise the risk of warm ischaemic injury to organs, it is recommended that the determination of circulatory death should occur no more than five minutes after circulatory arrest or withdrawal of cardiorespiratory support.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHowever, as this patient has an arterial line, a five minute observation of electrical asystole is not required. In some cases, ECG activity may persist (in some instances for \u0026gt;30 minutes) after circulatory arrest and cessation of pulsatile arterial blood pressure. Reliance on ECG activity may unnecessarily prolong the observation period and increase the risk of warm ischaemia. Thus, \u0022\u003Cstrong\u003Easystole for five minutes on an ECG\u003C/strong\u003E\u0022 is the correct answer (i.e. is NOT required for the diagnosis of circulatory death).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Circulatory death is defined by an absence of circulation for five minutes","Asystole on ECG is not required for determination of circulatory death if there is an arterial line in-situ"],"references":["The Australian and New Zealand Intensive Care Society. Statement on Death and Organ Donation. Edition 4.1. 2021 [cited 2024 March 23]. Available from: https://www.donatelife.gov.au/sites/default/files/2022-01/anzics-statement-on-death-and-organ-donation-4.1.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33869"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13549"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33869","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33869"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-19T08:33:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-03T10:39:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6164"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48874"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":